article.description: Diana Taurasi saw to it that Boston College had no chance to win on another buzzer-beater.
article.headline: Taurasi scores 18 of her 26 points in first half

images.name: Taurasi Diana 030330 vert inline
images.caption: Connecticut's Diana Taurasi is averaging 27.3 points in the NCAA Tournament.

article.linkText: Taurasi's quick start propels UConn into Elite Eight
article.story:
DAYTON, Ohio (AP) -- Diana Taurasi had it going from the start
and so did her Connecticut teammates. Boston College had no chance
to win on a buzzer-beater this time.

<photo1>Taurasi scored 18 of her 26 points in the first half and
Connecticut dominated from the start, beating Big East rival Boston
College 70-49 Sunday in the East Regional semifinals.

The top-seeded Huskies (34-1) shot 59 percent en route to a
19-point halftime lead and held BC to 32 percent shooting, ending
the Eagles' charmed run through the NCAA Tournament.

"I think in the first half that was probably the best we've run
our offense in a while,'' Taurasi said. "Everyone was touching the
ball, a lot of screens, a lot of cuts. That was probably one of the
best paces we've played at for a while.''

Connecticut, the defending national champion, will play Purdue
in the regional final Tuesday night. The Boilermakers beat Notre
Dame 66-47 in the other semifinal.

A victory in the regional final would send the Huskies to the
Final Four for the fourth straight year and seventh time overall.

Fifth-seeded Boston College (22-9) had advanced to the round of
16 for the first time by beating Old Dominion and Vanderbilt on
last-second shots by Amber Jacobs.

But with Taurasi scoring eight points, UConn closed the first
half with a 14-2 run to open a 44-25 lead. Boston College never
challenged the rest of the way -- a sharp contrast from the earlier
meeting, when UConn had to pull away late for an 83-75 victory.

"They're tough and so physical,'' Boston College forward Becky
Gottstein said. "It made maneuvering in the post so tough. You
always seemed to get a forearm in the back.''

Jessica Moore and Barbara Turner gave Connecticut an inside
presence, Moore scoring 17 points and Turner 14. Moore spearheaded
the defense against Gottstein, held to 10 points and five rebounds
with five turnovers.

"The coaches told me to just play hard, continue to run the
floor and play well,'' Moore said. "I just tried to do that.''

Jessalyn Deveny led BC with 14 points and Clare Droesch had 11.
Jacobs, who had averaged 24 points in the first two rounds, scored
only four on 2-for-13 shooting.

"BC did not play well today,'' UConn coach Geno Auriemma said.
"This was not the BC team that played the last two games. That had
an awful lot to do with it. The other part of it is I thought we
made them work so hard on the defensive end, especially their big
kids, that it took a lot out of them and on the offensive end, they
really had a hard time.''

But even another big game by Jacobs might not have saved the
Eagles, not the way Taurasi was playing.

Taurasi, coming off a career-high 35-point outing against TCU,
shot 10-for-17 and is now averaging 27.3 points for the tournament.
She was 2-of-5 from 3-point range, grabbed 12 rebounds and looked
good even when she missed.

Connecticut's run at the end of the first half started when
Taurasi faked a pass driving toward the basket and put up an
over-the-shoulder shot from the left side. She missed but was
fouled and made both free throws.

Taurasi hit a jumper off a screen the next time Connecticut had
the ball, then faked a 3-point shot, dribbled once and drilled a
17-footer. That made it 36-23 and the Huskies were on their way to
breaking it open.

"They have so many weapons and Taurasi is so good,'' BC coach
Cathy Inglese said. "She just took over. You need to have a leader
and impact player and she is that for them. It's difficult for me
to think anybody will beat them if they play like they did today.''

Boston College got no closer than 17 in the second half and
UConn went up 65-41 on Taurasi's baseline jumper with 6:21
remaining. She looked at the clock after swishing the shot, clapped
and laughed as she trotted back down the floor. With 4:51 left,
Taurasi went to the bench for good with UConn leading 65-44, a rest
well earned.

"You can't afford to have a bad game now,'' Taurasi said. "You
lose, you go home. You don't have a week to prepare for another
team. Knowing the situation we're in, we have to take advantage of
it. I personally don't want this season to end, not right now.''
